Part I - San Francisco Bike Share Data Exploration¶

by Secil Carver¶

Introduction¶

This document explores a dataset containing demographics, locations, and datetime attributes for approximately 180,000 bike-share riders.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are a little over 180,000 bike share entries in the original dataset with 16 variables (duration in seconds, start-time, end-time, start station id, name, latitude, longtitue, end station id, name, latitude, longtitude, bike id, user type, user birth year, user gender, bike share for all trip). Most variables are numeric in nature, with the exception of categorical entries such as user type, station name, and date/time. There are some unusual outliers in members' birth year, and ride duration in seconds which I will address.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am most interested in finding answers to: What are the demographics of the people that use the bike share service? What proportion of the customers that are subscribers? What is the busiest day of the week? How long do customer use the bikes for, and how far do they go with the bikes before returning them.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect the customer birth year, gender, start and end times will be most helpful to answer my questions of by whom, and when the bike share is used the most.

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, I will investigate the distributions of individual variables starting with customer age.

User Demographics¶

  • There are some outliers in the members birth years such as an entry of 1878. The amount of outliers are insignificant in numbers, however they do skew the graphs. I will remove them keeping the data within 5 standard deviation from the mean.
In [8]:
# keep only the ones that are within +5 to -5 standard deviations in the column 'member_birth_year'.
gobike = gobike[np.abs(gobike.member_birth_year-gobike.member_birth_year.mean()) <= (5*gobike.member_birth_year.std())]
In [9]:
# change data type of member_birth_year
gobike['member_birth_year'] = gobike['member_birth_year'].astype(int)

# create customer_age column and calculate customers' ages
today = 2022
gobike['customer_age'] = today - gobike['member_birth_year']

Duration of rides¶

  • The duration in seconds have outliers that are insignificant in numbers, however they do skew the graphs. I will remove them keeping data that is within 5 standard deviation from the mean. Then, I will create a duration in minutes column that gives a clearer picture of the duration of rides.

Distance traveled by riders¶

In [26]:
# create coordinates to calculate distance
gobike['start_coord'] = [', '.join(str(x) for x in y) 
                     for y in map(tuple, gobike[['start_station_latitude', 'start_station_longitude']].values)]
gobike['end_coord'] = [', '.join(str(x) for x in y) 
                     for y in map(tuple, gobike[['end_station_latitude', 'end_station_longitude']].values)]
In [27]:
# calculate distance traveled by riders
import geopy.distance
from geopy.distance import geodesic
def distance (row):
    start = (row['start_station_latitude'], row['start_station_longitude'])
    stop = (row['end_station_latitude'], row['end_station_longitude'])

    return geodesic(start, stop).miles
gobike['distance'] = gobike.apply (lambda row: distance(row),axis=1)
In [28]:
# drop the single outlier in distance column that is skewing the graph
gobike = gobike.drop(gobike[gobike.distance > 10].index)

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

At first glance the distance traveled for bikers were clustered around 1 mile because of an outlier. I changed the x-axis limit to 5 miles to get a closer look at the numbers.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I had to add columns like age, minutes, distance traveled, and calculate them accordingly. I eliminated outliers in membersbirth year by setting a limit to standard deviation of 5. I eliminated the single outlier in distance column which was skewing the data.

    plt.xlim(20,80)
    plt.xlabel('Age')
    plt.ylabel('Distance Traveled')
    plt.colorbar()
    plt.title('Rider Age and Distance Traveled')
age_distance()

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Upon closer inspection we can conclude male customers who are 26-42 years of age are the biggest bike renters. The busiest days/times for bike rentals are Tuesday and Thurday mornings. Weekends are not as busy as weekdays in general, although weekends afternoons are somewhat busier. The slowest rental times of the week are weekend mornings and evening. Time of day, and day of the week did not have any effect on the distance traveled on the bikes.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Most days had similar distances and rental durations at first glance. However, when I used 'log scale' for distance and duration in minutes a different view highlighted. Even though the bikes were used for longer distances during the week, the duration of the rentals were not that long. And conversely on the weekends, even though the bikes were rented to go shorter distances, the duration of the rentals were much longer than bike rental durations during the week.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Out of the 329 bike stations, 7 of them have more riders than others. Riders in these stations are more concentrated on the weekdays.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Subscribers age average is slightly more than casual customers' age average. Surprisingly the average age among users (Customer and Subscriber) were lower on the weekends than during the week. Also, female riders were more prevelant on the weekends, male riders are more prevelant during the week. Some interactions such as day of the week, duration and distance did not provide any useful information using multivariate graphing. Bivariate graphs were more useful to explore that data.

Conclusions¶

Out of close to 180,000 rider data from 329 bike stations, I was able extract some insights regarding the customers and their choices. Most of the riders were Subscribers. Most of the riders were male between the ages of 26-42, with a mean of 37. Most riders used the bikes during the week for less than 10 minutes, to go a distance of 1 mile or less. There were 7 bike stations that were frequented by over 2,500 riders in the month of February, the mean riders per bike station is about 1,000. There were more female riders on the weekends, and more male riders during the week.
